Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pour a good glug of @olive oil{} onto a #baking tray{} and pop in your oven. Bring a #large saucepan{} of water to the boil on high heat with @salt{0.5%tsp}. Peel the @potatoes{900%g}, chop them into 4cm chunks. Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife. Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan then sprinkle on half the @plain flour{24%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potato. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven until golden for ~{45-50%minutes}, turning halfway through.

Season the @lamb roasting joint{450%g} with @salt{}, @ground black pepper{} and a drizzle of @olive oil{}. Transfer to another baking tray and roast in the oven for ~{30-55%minutes} (depending on size) for medium rare. Add an extra 5 mins if you like your lamb more cooked. Rest wrapped loosely in #foil{} for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing. Meanwhile, trim and halve the @chantenay carrots{250%g} lengthways (no need to peel). Place onto a baking tray, drizzle with @olive oil{} and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Toss to coat then spread out in a single layer. Roast until golden and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, pick the @mint{1%sprig} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Roughly chop the @capers{15%g}. Zest and halve the @lemon{1}. Pop the capers, mint, @olive oil{1.5%tbsp} and half the lemon juice in a #small bowl{}. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, mix well and set aside.

Pop a #saucepan{} on a medium heat and add half the @unsalted butter{30%g}, allow it to melt, then stir in the remaining @plain flour{}. You've made a roux! Cook until the roux is a medium-brown colour and gradually stir in the @water{400%ml} and @chicken stock paste{1}. Bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that form. Lower the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Heat a #frying pan{} over medium-high heat with the remaining butter. Once melted, add the garlic and cook, stirring for ~{1%minute}, then add the @shredded savoy cabbage{150%g} and stir-fry for ~{2%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, add a splash of @water{} and a pinch of @lemon zest{}, mix well and cover with a #lid{} (or some foil) and cook until just tender, ~{3-4%minutes}. Once cooked, remove from the heat then squeeze some lemon juice in and stir through the roasted carrots.

Reheat the gravy if needed, adding any resting juices from the lamb and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} to taste. Slice the lamb and divide between plates. Divide the potatoes and cabbage with carrots between the plates. Drizzle the salsa verde over the lamb and serve with the gravy. Enjoy!